<paragraph blockId="1.[151,529,1504,1531]" box="[151,529,1504,1531]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,529,1504,1531]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,529,1504,1531]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
Key to the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Townes &amp; Townes" authorityYear="1950" box="[412,529,1504,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Scolomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[412,529,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Scolomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="191" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1575,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="190">1 Mandible stout with small acuminate teeth of the same length. Labrum apex always visible, even with mandibles closed. Wings with a pentagonal areolet, veins 2RS and rs-m touching 3RSa separately. Subtegular ridge produced as a sharp, curved spine. Deep groove between the propodeum and metanotum................................................... 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1575,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
- Mandible slender with upper tooth distinctly longer than the lower tooth. Labrum more or less concealed when mandibles closed (
<figureCitation box="[270,330,1693,1714]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1391,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1391,1885]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Scolomus clypeatus new species. 1: holotype female, head (frontal view); 2: holotype female, habitus. Scale bars (mm): Figs 1 = 0.4; Figs 2 = 2.0." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1279848/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[343,381,1693,1714]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1427,1450]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,411,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,411,1406]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3–6. Scolomus maculatus new species. Figs 3: holotype female, head (frontal view); 4: holotype female, habitus; Figs 5: paratype male, head (frontal view); 6: paratype male, habitus. Scale bars (mm): Figs 3 and 5 = 0.4; Figs 4 and 6 = 2.0." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1279850/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">3, 5</figureCitation>
). Areolet slightly petiolate, rhombic, with 2RS vein joining rs-m shortly before touching 3RSa (
<figureCitation box="[1312,1375,1693,1714]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1391,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1391,1885]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Scolomus clypeatus new species. 1: holotype female, head (frontal view); 2: holotype female, habitus. Scale bars (mm): Figs 1 = 0.4; Figs 2 = 2.0." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1279848/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1385,1421,1693,1714]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1427,1450]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,411,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,411,1406]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3–6. Scolomus maculatus new species. Figs 3: holotype female, head (frontal view); 4: holotype female, habitus; Figs 5: paratype male, head (frontal view); 6: paratype male, habitus. Scale bars (mm): Figs 3 and 5 = 0.4; Figs 4 and 6 = 2.0." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1279850/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">4, 6</figureCitation>
). Subtegular ridge not produced as a sharp spine. Shallow groove between the propodeum and metanotum................ 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1575,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
2(1) Propodeum without areola, posterior transverse carina incomplete. Lateral longitudinal carina sharper and more distinct near propodeal spiracle............................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Walkley 1962" authorityName="Walkley (Andean" authorityYear="1962" box="[1145,1436,1781,1802]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Scolomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magellanicus">
<emphasis box="[1145,1157,1781,1802]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1169,1297,1781,1802]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">magellanicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1302,1436,1781,1802]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" refId="ref4653" refString="Walkley, L. M. (1962) A second species of Ichneumonidae belonging to Scolomus Townes (Hymenoptera). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 64, 231 - 233." type="journal article">Walkley 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1575,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
- Propodeum with areola delimited by the lateromedian longitudinal, anterior and posterior transverse carinae. Lateral longitudinal carina faint, indistinct near propodeal spiracle.................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Townes &amp; Townes 1950" authorityName="Townes &amp; Townes" authorityYear="1950" box="[1111,1436,1839,1860]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Scolomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viridis">
<emphasis box="[1111,1123,1839,1860]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1135,1196,1839,1860]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">viridis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[1203,1436,1839,1860]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" refId="ref4562" refString="Townes, H. K. &amp; Townes, M. (1950) A revision of the genera and of the American species of Tryphoninae Part II. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 42, 397 - 447. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 42.4.397" type="journal article">Townes &amp; Townes 1950</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1575,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
3(1) Propodeum with no trace of lateromedian longitudinal carina. Head and mesoscutum with reddish brown marks, fore leg orange brown. Central America............................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gauld &amp; Sithole 2002)" authorityName="Gauld &amp; Sithole" authorityYear="2002" baseAuthorityName="Gauld &amp; Sithole" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[1071,1429,1898,1919]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Scolomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="talamanca">
<emphasis box="[1071,1083,1898,1919]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1095,1196,1898,1919]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">talamanca</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[1209,1423,1898,1919]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" refId="ref4332" refString="Gauld, I. D., Sithole, R., Gomez, J. U. &amp; Godoy, C. (2002) The Ichneumonidae of Costa Rica 4. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 66, 1 - 768." type="journal article">Gauld &amp; Sithole 2002</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1575,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="190">- Propodeum with lateromedian longitudinal carina discernible. Head and mesoscutum without reddish brown marks, fore leg brown or green...................................................................................... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="191" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1575,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="190">
4(3) Body mostly blackish, without extensive green areas. Female supra-clypeal area with simple, uniformly distributed setae. Propodeum with lateral longitudinal carina incomplete. Holarctic........................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Townes 1971)" authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1971" baseAuthorityName="Townes" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[1184,1436,2015,2036]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Apolophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[1184,1196,2015,2036]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1208,1285,2015,2036]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="190">borealis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[1298,1429,2015,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="190" refId="ref4532" refString="Townes, H. K. (1971) The genera of Ichneumonidae, Part 4. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 17, 1 - 372." type="journal article">Townes 1971</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="191">- Body with extensive green areas. Female supra-clypeal area with clusters of seemingly bifurcate setae. Propodeum with lateral longitudinal carina complete. Chile...................................................................... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
5(4) Clypeus width 3.00× its height (
<figureCitation box="[543,601,210,231]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1391,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1391,1885]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Scolomus clypeatus new species. 1: holotype female, head (frontal view); 2: holotype female, habitus. Scale bars (mm): Figs 1 = 0.4; Figs 2 = 2.0." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1279848/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Distance between eye and lateral ocellus 1.50× diameter of lateral ocellus. Areolet 0.80× as wide as long. Hypopygium 1.55× as long as wide, in lateral view. Ovipositor 12.50× as long as basal width. Head, mesoscutum, postscutellum and pronotum entirely brownish yellow............................. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1236,1436,268,290]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<taxonomicName authority="Araujo &amp; Vivallo &amp; Santos, 2018" authorityName="Araujo &amp; Vivallo &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2018" box="[1236,1353,268,290]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Scolomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clypeatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1236,1249,268,290]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1261,1353,268,290]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">clypeatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1359,1436,268,290]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
- Clypeus width 1.55×–2.30× its height (
<figureCitation box="[611,697,298,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–6" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1427,1450]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,411,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,411,1406]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3–6. Scolomus maculatus new species. Figs 3: holotype female, head (frontal view); 4: holotype female, habitus; Figs 5: paratype male, head (frontal view); 6: paratype male, habitus. Scale bars (mm): Figs 3 and 5 = 0.4; Figs 4 and 6 = 2.0." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1279850/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Fig. 3, 5</figureCitation>
). Distance between eye and lateral ocellus 0.90×–1.00× diameter of lateral ocellus. Areolet 1.00× as wide as long. Hypopygium 1.90× as long as wide, in lateral view. Ovipositor 5.30× as long as basal width. Head and pronotum greenish, mesoscutum yellow with dark brown spots on lateral lobes and around scutellum......................................................................................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1225,1436,386,408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<taxonomicName authority="Araujo &amp; Vivallo &amp; Santos, 2018" authorityName="Araujo &amp; Vivallo &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2018" box="[1225,1353,386,408]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Scolomus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1225,1238,386,408]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1251,1353,386,408]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1359,1436,386,408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
